{"metadata":{"kernelspec":{"language":"python","display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"},"language_info":{"name":"python","version":"3.11.15","mimetype":"text/x-python","codemirror_mode":{"name":"ipython","version":3},"pygments_lexer":"ipython3","nbconvert_exporter":"python","file_extension":".py"},"kaggle":{"accelerator":"none","dataSources":[{"sourceType":"modelInstanceVersion","sourceId":806899,"databundleVersionId":16319088,"modelInstanceId":611371,"modelId":623192}],"dockerImageVersionId":31330,"isInternetEnabled":true,"language":"python","sourceType":"notebook","isGpuEnabled":false}},"nbformat_minor":4,"nbformat":4,"cells":[{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"🎯 Objective\nDetect whether the model memorizes exact proximity or learns distributed patterns in feature space.\n\n🔬 Methodology\nSplit the training set into subsets of increasing density (n=10, 20, 50, 100, 200)\nFor each split: compute epsilon (20th percentile of D_tt)\nMeasure how the average number of neighbors in the VR ball changes as n grows\nIf learning: neighbors ↑ smoothly with n (generalizable pattern)\nIf memorization: neighbors ↑↑ sharply or concentrate in a cluster (overfitting)\n\n📋 Prompt Definition\n\nPROMPT_1_LEARNING_VS_MEMORIZATION = \nH7 Benchmark — Prompt 1: Distance Generalization Probe\n═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n[MODE]: Density-Growth Sensitivity\n\nPROCEDURE:\n──────────\n\nCreate progressive training splits:\n\nsplit_10  = random subsample(n=10)\nsplit_20  = random subsample(n=20)\nsplit_50  = random subsample(n=50)\nsplit_100 = random subsample(n=100)\nsplit_200 = random subsample(n=200)\n\nFor each split:\na) Compute precision matrix VI from split\nb) Compute D_tt (dual-distance train-to-train)\nc) Calibrate epsilon at 20th percentile\nd) For each test instance, measure |neighbors in VR-ball|\ne) Report: mean_neighbors, std_neighbors, epsilon\n\nANALYSIS TABLE:\n┌─────────────┬──────────┬──────────┬──────────┬─────────────┐\n│ Split Size  │ Epsilon  │ Avg Neig │ Std Neig │ Trend       │\n├─────────────┼──────────┼──────────┼──────────┼─────────────┤\n│      10     │  {eps}   │  {m_n}   │  {s_n}   │   —         │\n│      20     │  {eps}   │  {m_n}   │  {s_n}   │ ↑ linear?   │\n│      50     │  {eps}   │  {m_n}   │  {s_n}   │ ↑ smooth?   │\n│     100     │  {eps}   │  {m_n}   │  {s_n}   │ ↑ saturate? │\n│     200     │  {eps}   │  {m_n}   │  {s_n}   │ plateau     │\n└─────────────┴──────────┴──────────┴──────────┴─────────────┘\n\nINTERPRETATION CRITERIA:\n─────────────────────────\n✓ LEARNING SIGNAL:\n\n  Mean neighbors grows logarithmically or as root(n)\n  Epsilon increases but stays bounded\n  Std neighbors remains stable\n  → Pattern generalizes across larger datasets\n\n✗ MEMORIZATION SIGNAL:\n\n  Mean neighbors grows faster than O(log n) or O(√n)\n  Epsilon explodes or collapses to near-zero on any split\n  Std neighbors spikes (indicating instability)\n  → Model overfits to proximity structure of specific subset\n  \nEXPECTED OUTPUT:\n────────────────\nFor {category}:\nTrend: [LINEAR | LOGARITHMIC | ROOT | SUBLINEAR | EXPONENTIAL]\nStability Score: [0.0–1.0] (1.0 = consistent across splits)\nMemorization Risk: [LOW | MEDIUM | HIGH]\nRecommendation: [INCREASE ALPHA | ADJUST EPSILON | VALIDATE FEATURES]\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# 📚 LEARNING RESOURCES\n# Quick Start: https://github.com/Kaggle/kaggle-benchmarks/blob/ci/quick_start.md\n# Cookbook:    https://github.com/Kaggle/kaggle-benchmarks/blob/ci/cookbook.md\n# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nimport kaggle_benchmarks as kbench\n\n# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# STEP 1: DEFINE YOUR TASK\n# The @task decorator turns a standard Python function into a Benchmark task.\n# The first parameter must always be `llm` (the model being tested).\n# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n@kbench.task(name=\"attention\", description=\"Does the LLM is learning or generalizing?\")\ndef what_is_kaggle(llm) -> None:\n\n    # A. Prompt the model\n    response: str = llm.prompt(\"What is Kaggle?\")\n\n    # B. Simple Check (Hard Rule)\n    # Fast and cheap: Ensure specific keywords exist in the output.\n    kbench.assertions.assert_in(\"platform\", response.lower())\n\n    # C. Optional Advanced Check (LLM Judge)\n    # Use a helper LLM to evaluate the quality of the answer against criteria.\n    assessment = kbench.assertions.assess_response_with_judge(\n        response_text=response,\n        judge_llm=kbench.judge_llm,\n        criteria=[\n            \"The answer must mention data science or machine learning.\",\n            \"The answer should mention competitions.\",\n        ]\n    )\n\n    # Iterate through the judge's feedback and assert success\n    for result in assessment.results:\n        kbench.assertions.assert_true(\n            result.passed,\n            expectation=f\"Judge Criterion '{result.criterion}' should pass: {result.reason}\"\n        )\n\n# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# STEP 2: RUN THE TASK\n# We use `kbench.llm` as a placeholder. This allows Kaggle to automatically swap\n# in different models later when you use the \"Add Models\" button in the UI.\n# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\nwhat_is_kaggle.run(kbench.llm)\n\n# Note: To test a specific model locally, you can use the dictionary lookup:\nwhat_is_kaggle.run(kbench.llms[\"google/gemini-2.0-flash\"])\n\n# --------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n# STEP 3: NEXT STEPS\n# 1. Click \"Save Task\" (top right) to publish to the leaderboard.\n# 2. Try `%autopilot` in a new cell to auto-generate tasks or write your own!\n# -----------------------